# DevOps Interview Prep — Scenario-Based Questions

A quick-reference cheat sheet for common DevOps interview scenarios.

---

## 1. Staging works, prod fails sometimes
- Compare staging vs prod setup (configs, secrets, versions)
- Check if it happens under real traffic/load
- Look at logs during the exact failure time
- Think: "what's different in prod?"

## 2. Dev wants to skip the pipeline
- Say no — pipeline exists to catch bugs early
- Ask why it's slow, fix that instead
- Speed up: caching, parallel tests, smaller checks
- Protect the process, don't remove it

## 3. Manual steps in deployment
- Automate the riskiest/most repeated step first
- Priority = high risk + high frequency
- Don't just pick the "easy" one

## 4. Errors in prod, cause unknown
- Go broad → narrow
- Check: recent changes → infra health → config → app logs
- Change one thing at a time to isolate cause

## 5. Release caused downtime, rollback risky too
- Compare: current damage vs rollback risk
- If users are badly affected → rollback/disable feature
- Always have a tested rollback plan ready in advance

## 6. Cloud cost spiked after release
- Check new/unused resources
- Check autoscaling triggers
- Check inefficient code (loops, queries)
- Compare cost before vs after release

## 7. Security scan blocking release
- Don't bypass security
- Sort issues by severity
- Block only critical/high risk
- Fix low-risk ones later, track them

## 8. Teams using different tool versions
- Standardize using IaC / shared config
- Add CI check to catch version mismatch
- One source of truth for versions

## 9. Alerts during peak traffic
- Check if real users are impacted (latency/errors)
- If system handled peak fine → it's noise
- Adjust alert thresholds based on normal peak data

## 10. Leadership wants speed, team wants stability
- Speed and stability aren't opposites
- Use automation: CI/CD, canary release, feature flags
- Smaller, frequent releases = safer AND faster

---

**Quick memory trick:**
Every answer follows the same pattern —
**Compare → Isolate → Prioritize by risk → Automate → Don't cut corners on safety.**
